# Git workflow

## Agent GitHub identity

Agent sessions run under the mise `agent` env (`MISE_ENV=agent` / launcher aliases), so
`gh` and GitHub-MCP actions on github.com are attributed to the agent machine user
({{ .my.github_agent.username }}); commit author stays the human. Escape hatches:
`env -u GH_TOKEN <cmd>` acts as the human for one command; `mise x -E agent -- <cmd>`
acts as the agent from an unswitched session.

## Commits

- Conventional Commits: semantic subject + audit-useful rationale in the body.
- One logical change per commit: touch only the files required for that change;
  commit independent concerns separately.
- Outside plan mode, auto-commit completed work without asking — commits flow
  automatically in implementation mode. **Never ask the user to approve a routine
  worktree commit**, including after a correction; incorporate it and commit. Return to
  plan mode only when a fundamental design decision requires user alignment.
- Commit/PR audit trailers (Authored-By, Model, Session-ID, …) → my-audit-trail.

## Push / pull

- Push immediately after every commit, same turn — don't wait to be asked.
- Pull-rebase-before-push: always `git pull --rebase` before `git push`; on a
  non-fast-forward rejection, retry once with `git pull --rebase && git push`.
- Auto-proceed on read-only ops (status, diff, log, show, branch, pull, push,
  push --force-with-lease) without asking.

## Destructive ops — pause first

Pause before push --force, push --delete, rebase, reset, stash pop/drop, tag
unless the user explicitly requested that exact action in the current message.

**Tidy your own worktree branch without pausing.** The pause-first rule above guards *shared* history. When you are inside your own isolated worktree, on a branch only you have touched, `git rebase` (onto / interactive) to reshape your commits and `git push --force-with-lease` to update your own PR only rewrite work you created — run them without pausing and never hand them to the user (e.g. rebasing onto `origin/main` to drop stray commits before review).

This carve-out does **not** relax the main-branch rules: never advance or merge `main` without explicit approval, and never bare `push --force` / `-f` — `--force-with-lease` only.

## Stashes

Always `git stash push -m "<unique-slug>"` — never bare `git stash`. Pop by name.
Multiple agents share the stash stack; unnamed stashes collide.

## Uncommitted edits already on main → stash into a worktree

The user sometimes edits files directly on `main` and asks you to review and commit them.
Commits on the main checkout are hook-blocked. **Do not** request a `worktree-exempt` file —
move the changes into a worktree via the shared stash stack:

1. **Create a worktree** (create mechanics below). cwd is now the worktree, so git against the
   main checkout is allowed via `git -C <main>` (`<main>` = parent of `git rev-parse --git-common-dir`).
2. **Stash main's changes:** `git -C <main> stash push -m "<slug>"` — named per `## Stashes`,
   guard-inert because cwd is the worktree. Main's working tree is now clean.
3. **Pull them into the worktree:** `git stash list` to find the `stash@{n}` matching `<slug>`,
   then `git stash apply stash@{n}`. The stash stack is shared via the common git dir.
4. **Review, commit in the worktree, and merge back** per the protocol below.
5. **After the commit is verified,** `git -C <main> stash drop stash@{n}`. Apply-then-drop keeps
   the stash as a backup until the commit lands; `pop` would discard it on the spot.

- *Stash won't apply cleanly* (local main was ahead of origin and the worktree branched fresh):
  resolve the conflicts, or recreate the worktree from local `HEAD` so the edits apply onto the
  state they were made against.

## Multi-instance worktrees (mandatory before any file edit)

Concurrent agents on one branch race (last write wins); Write/Edit/Bash are
hook-blocked on the main checkout until inside a worktree.

1. `git pull`, then check claims: `todo.sh list @worktree`.
2. Create a worktree and work inside it.
3. Record the claim in todo.txt and commit it in the worktree's first commit.
   ← todo.txt format: my-task-tracking.

### Completing the worktree — merge-back

The worktree guard only restricts git whose **cwd is the main checkout**. So run every step
below from **inside the worktree** (where all git is allowed) and advance main via
`git -C <main> …` — the guard stays inert and the whole flow is agent-doable. The only
human-only action is creating a `worktree-exempt` file; never create one. `<main>` = the
primary checkout (the parent of `git rev-parse --git-common-dir`).

1. **Test.** Run the project's automated gates (e.g. `mise run lint && mise run test`, or the
   repo's equivalents) and fix failures — see `my-linting`, `my-testing`.

2. **Fresh self-review.** Have a fresh sub-agent review the implementation per `my-code-review`.
   Address findings and repeat until no significant findings remain (`my-execution` owns this loop).

3. **Implementation commit and push.** Commit only the reviewed implementation, then pull-rebase and
   push it. This is distinct from the task-record bookkeeping commit that follows.

4. **Archive the exact completed task.** Before PR-ready/final handoff, the owning agent moves the
   exact completed todo.txt record (including all metadata) to done.txt with an `x YYYY-MM-DD` prefix.
   Non-owning subagents report completion only. Never infer completion from a shared PR, session,
   worktree, or commit.

5. **Bookkeeping commit and push.** Commit and push the task-record move separately from the
   implementation commit.

6. **PR-ready/final handoff — before any merge.** First freshen: `git -C <main> pull --rebase`, then
   rebase your branch onto latest main and resolve conflicts. (If a push is rejected non-fast-forward,
   retry the rebase once, then surface.) Then:
   - *GitHub:* create or update the draft (`gh pr create --draft --fill` if needed), then run
     `gh pr ready`. This is **not optional** for a completed, deploy-ready change. Leave the PR **open**;
     surface its URL and a short "what to review" note. Do **not** run `gh pr merge`.
   - *Local / no remote:* **stop** — do not advance main. Tell me the branch is ready and summarize
     what to review.

7. **Reviewer feedback loop.** When the human leaves PR review comments: reply on each
   thread once addressed (say what changed + the commit), or reply first when there are
   important considerations to discuss before changing code. Resume work in the kept
   worktree for fixes. **Never resolve review threads** — the human resolves each thread
   after verifying it was addressed.

8. **Merge only on my explicit approval, and only what's expected to deploy.** `main` reflects prod:
   never merge a change you don't expect to ship (here, to be `chezmoi apply`-ied). If it isn't
   deploy-ready, keep it a draft / on the branch.
   - *Repos I own ({{ .my.github_personal_owners | join ", " }}):* after I approve in-session,
     squash-merge. GitHub → `gh pr merge --squash --delete-branch`, then `git -C <main> pull --rebase`,
     and delete the local branch with `git branch -D <branch>` (squash leaves it "unmerged", so `-d`
     refuses). Local → `git -C <main> pull --rebase` (if it has a remote), `git -C <main> merge --squash
     <branch>` + one conventional commit, `git -C <main> push` (if it has a remote), then
     `git branch -D <branch>`.
   - *Work / shared (owner not mine):* I merge through the org's process; the agent never merges these.
   - *Unrecognized origin:* gather the facts (remote URL, owner, is it yours?), ask me how to
     integrate, then propose a `my-git` update so it's covered next time (see `my-agent-memory`).

9. **Cleanup — after an approved merge only.** Keep the worktree until the change is merged (I may
   request changes — resume in it). Then delete the local branch (step 8) and remove the worktree with
   the harness-specific mechanism below. Automatic cleanup is harness-specific and not available in every
   harness; no agent may treat it as authoritative task completion. The owner must archive the exact task
   in step 4 before PR-ready/final handoff. (A squash-merge isn't a fast-forward, so the explicit
   `git branch -D` is what clears the branch.)

